efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(N)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW 
explanation: The solution uses a sliding window approach. It iterates through the string, maintaining a count of vowels within the current window. If the vowel count is not valid (i.e., not all vowels have an even count), the window is shrunk from the left until a valid substring is found. The maximum length of a valid substring is tracked and returned. This approach ensures linear time complexity as each character is visited at most twice (once during expansion and once during contraction of the window). Space complexity is constant as the data structures used are of fixed size.

